WEBVTT

00:00:01.780 --> 00:00:05.219
Well, brothers and sisters, hasn't this been an amazing program?

00:00:06.780 --> 00:00:20.670
This is truly a historic day in the history of Jehovah's Witnesses.

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:28.269
And maybe our hearts right now are more full of love and appreciation for our wonderful God, Jehovah,

00:00:28.269 --> 00:00:37.869
than ever before. We've deepened our understanding of Jehovah's mercy, his compassion, and his patience.

00:00:38.829 --> 00:00:42.429
And what about that announcement about our field service reporting?

00:00:43.789 --> 00:00:52.990
Jehovah is dignifying us. He has confidence in us. You see, why do we go from house to house?

00:00:53.710 --> 00:01:00.670
Why do we do cart work? Why do we make telephone calls and write letters and make return visits and

00:01:00.670 --> 00:01:07.790
start Bible studies? Why do we do all of these things? It's because we truly

00:01:08.189 --> 00:01:16.030
love our amazing and wonderful God, Jehovah. As Brother Flegal emphasized in his talk,

00:01:16.829 --> 00:01:24.590
at Matthew 22 and verse 37, Jesus identified the greatest and first commandment. Do you remember what

00:01:24.590 --> 00:01:34.109
he said? You must love Jehovah your God with your whole heart and with your whole soul and with

00:01:34.189 --> 00:01:42.189
your whole mind. But is there something else that moves us to make disciples? Yes.

00:01:43.950 --> 00:01:51.870
It's what Jesus said was the second greatest commandment. Jesus said, you must love your neighbor

00:01:52.670 --> 00:02:03.469
as yourself. So we must love God, but we must also love people. Now, why is love for people so

00:02:03.469 --> 00:02:14.270
important? Well, because when we see that someone cares about us, we are moved even if we don't know

00:02:14.270 --> 00:02:20.270
that person. For example, maybe someone you've never met before does a kind deed for you. Maybe

00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:26.110
they open a door for you. They pick something up that you've dropped or they help you carry a heavy

00:02:26.189 --> 00:02:34.110
load. How do you feel? Well, you appreciate their kindness, don't you? And as a result, you're more

00:02:34.110 --> 00:02:41.949
inclined to want to listen to what that person might want to say to you. You see, when we sense

00:02:42.830 --> 00:02:54.110
that someone has love for us, we open up our hearts. Well, unselfish love is so powerful. It

00:02:54.110 --> 00:03:03.150
touches the hearts of those who are rightly disposed for everlasting life. And Jesus said that his

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:11.389
true disciples would be identified. They'd be recognized by the love that they had in their midst.

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:18.430
Well, isn't it true that so often brothers and sisters say that what it was that drew them to

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:25.229
the truth was the love they felt from their Bible teacher or from the congregation when they

00:03:25.229 --> 00:03:34.349
began to attend meetings. Well, very likely, that same love was what drew you to want to become

00:03:34.349 --> 00:03:42.509
a disciple of Christ Jesus. Well, for that reason, at the 2017 annual meeting, the governing body

00:03:42.509 --> 00:03:50.189
encouraged us to begin to think more about conversing with people. And at that same meeting,

00:03:50.189 --> 00:03:57.469
you remember we simplified our teaching toolbox so that we could become more familiar with the

00:03:57.469 --> 00:04:05.710
various tools that we use in the ministry. You see, we want to carefully consider each individual's

00:04:06.509 --> 00:04:14.509
personal situation, the concerns that they have, the interests that they have, and then be flexible

00:04:14.509 --> 00:04:22.350
in choosing a topic that we want to discuss with them. Well, for several years now, our midweek meetings

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:30.110
have provided us with sample conversations, with suggested scriptures, and even with a suggested

00:04:31.069 --> 00:04:38.990
link to help us to continue the conversation at a later time. But is there a challenge sometimes

00:04:38.990 --> 00:04:46.029
with a memorized presentation? You know, I think back when I was a brand new pioneer, one day I was

00:04:46.029 --> 00:04:50.430
out with his sister in the ministry. As we were going to the door, you know, she was actually

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:56.990
mouthing her presentation. She had it perfectly memorized. And suddenly this woman came to the door,

00:04:56.990 --> 00:05:02.189
she opened the door, and here she was, beautiful older lady, hair done, makeup on, beautifully

00:05:02.189 --> 00:05:07.470
dressed, looking like she was just going out. The sister was so flustered, she said, oh, I'm sorry,

00:05:07.470 --> 00:05:25.870
did we get you out of bed? Yeah, memorized presentations. Not always good. Well, maybe we've memorized

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:32.189
presentations. And sometimes we felt like we're giving a talk when we're at the door. But what if the

00:05:32.189 --> 00:05:38.350
person has a very specific interest? What if they have some special need or they're facing some

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:45.149
terrible challenge just at the time when we're calling? Well, we want to look to the example of our

00:05:45.149 --> 00:05:53.870
Lord Jesus Christ. He set the perfect example for us. He showed love for people by choosing subjects

00:05:53.870 --> 00:06:01.709
that were appropriate for each individual and his personal interest in individuals attracted

00:06:01.709 --> 00:06:08.029
people to the message. Well, for example, do you remember the time when Jesus had a conversation

00:06:08.029 --> 00:06:15.790
with the Pharisee Nicodemus? Now, Nicodemus was impressed by Jesus' miracles, and he approached

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:23.310
Jesus at night probably because he was afraid of the Jews. Now, as a Pharisee and a teacher,

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:29.389
Nicodemus evidently must have had a very great knowledge of the Hebrew scriptures. So what did

00:06:29.389 --> 00:06:37.310
Jesus do? Well, he shared something with Nicodemus that was completely new. You see, he talked about new

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:45.069
truths about being born again and about seeing the kingdom of God. He explained to Nicodemus that he

00:06:45.069 --> 00:06:52.430
had descended from the heavens and that he was the only begotten Son of God and that he was the way

00:06:53.389 --> 00:06:59.550
to everlasting life. Well, I'm sure you'd agree that even though Nicodemus was a teacher,

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:08.110
he received quite an education from Jesus on that night. But now, does that mean that Jesus took

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:15.230
exactly that same approach with everyone that he met? Well, no, not at all. You see, on another

00:07:15.230 --> 00:07:21.069
occasion, when Jesus spoke to the Samaritan woman, his approach was completely different.

00:07:21.949 --> 00:07:27.310
Evidently, the Samaritan woman had a very basic knowledge of the Hebrew scriptures.

00:07:27.949 --> 00:07:34.110
So what did Jesus do? Well, he noted the things she was interested in like obtaining water

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:41.629
and why Jesus, as a Jew, would speak with a Samaritan. Well, Jesus also took an interest

00:07:41.629 --> 00:07:48.269
in her family situation. He noted that she was very concerned about why did Jews

00:07:48.269 --> 00:07:54.509
worship in one location and Samaritans in a different location? What did Jesus do?

00:07:55.149 --> 00:08:00.829
Well, he talked with her about the things that interested her that were of concern to her. He

00:08:00.829 --> 00:08:07.709
helped her to see that worshiping was spirit and truth was more important than the location

00:08:07.709 --> 00:08:14.829
where individuals would worship. And how did that woman respond? Well, the Bible says she left

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:22.110
her water jar there at the well. She went into the city and she gave a powerful witness about Jesus.

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:30.029
She was so effective that the Samaritans invited Jesus to stay and many put faith in him.

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:38.429
So now, what do we learn from these two simple accounts? Well, Jesus did not use a memorized

00:08:38.429 --> 00:08:45.470
presentation. He just talked with people and he shared with them the truths that he knew

00:08:45.470 --> 00:08:53.549
would touch their hearts. He was very quick to choose topics and words based on the interests

00:08:53.549 --> 00:09:01.629
and the concerns of the person that he was speaking to. Well, now, with all of this in mind,

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:12.899
you may be wondering what you're supposed to be wondering. How can I display that same love for

00:09:12.899 --> 00:09:18.580
the people that I meet? See, wouldn't it be wonderful to have a little bit more help to see how we

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:25.539
can show love for people and make disciples? See, wouldn't it be wonderful to have a publication

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:32.740
that would help us to be more flexible and more responsive to the different needs and interests

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:40.419
of the people that we meet? And what if that publication highlighted specific ways

00:09:40.419 --> 00:09:47.460
that Jesus and other first century evangelizers showed their love as they made disciples?

00:09:48.419 --> 00:09:59.200
Well, you will be happy to know that Jehovah's organization has produced just such a publication.

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:05.600
It's a 32-page brochure entitled, Love People Make Disciples.

00:10:33.629 --> 00:10:39.629
But now, would you like to see a little preview of what this brochure contains? Please watch

00:10:39.629 --> 00:10:48.720
the following video. This new publication, Love People Make Disciples, is being made available in

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:56.320
both print and digital formats in over 400 languages. How is the brochure designed to help us show

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:04.000
love for people we meet? Unlike the tools we've used in the past, this new brochure

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.600
does not give us expressions to memorize, nor does it put the emphasis on leaving literature.

00:11:12.179 --> 00:11:18.419
